<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Manual"><PMID Version="1">29458936</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2018</Year><Month>08</Month><Day>20</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2025</Year><Month>06</Month><Day>23</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print-Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1873-6963</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>36</Volume><PubDate><Year>2018</Year><Month>Feb</Month></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>Complementary therapies in medicine</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Complement Ther Med</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Effects of combined and resistance training on the inflammatory profile in breast cancer survivors: A systematic review.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>73</StartPage><EndPage>81</EndPage><MedlinePgn>73-81</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1016/j.ctim.2017.11.023</ELocationID><ELocationID EIdType="pii" ValidYN="Y">S0965-2299(17)30461-2</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText Label="OBJECTIVE" NlmCategory="OBJECTIVE">The present systematic review aimed to verify the effect of resistance and combined training on the inflammatory profile of breast cancer survivors.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="DESIGN" NlmCategory="METHODS">The searches were made on the platforms PsycINFO, PubMed, Cochrane, Science Direct and Scopus, from 1996 to 2017, using the keywords: cancer survivors, cancer treatment, cancer patients, breast cancer, inflammation, inflammatory profile, immune function, resistance training, strength training, weight training, physical activity, concurrent training and combined training. References of selected articles were also considered. Seven studies fulfilled the criteria adopted for analysis.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="RESULTS" NlmCategory="RESULTS">None of these studies have shown reduced inflammatory markers in breast cancer survivors undergoing combined or isolated resistance training.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="CONCLUSIONS" NlmCategory="CONCLUSIONS">It is not yet possible to conclude which resistance and/or combination training protocol is capable of improving the short-term inflammatory profile in this population. Future studies should seek to establish how structural training variables (intensity, volume, density, intra- and inter-series recovery, among others) act on anti-inflammatory processes in breast cancer survivors.</AbstractText><CopyrightInformation>Copyright &#xa9; 2017 Elsevier Ltd. All rights reserved.</CopyrightInformation></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>de Jesus Leite</LastName><ForeName>Marco Aur&#xe9;lio Ferreira</ForeName><Initials>MAF</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Institute of Genetics and Biochemistry, Federal University of Uberlandia, Uberlandia, MG, Brazil. Electronic address: marcoferreiraleite@hotmail.com.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Puga</LastName><ForeName>Guilherme Morais</ForeName><Initials>GM</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Faculty of Physical Education and Physiotherapy, Federal University of Uberlandia, Uberlandia, MG, Brazil. Electronic address: gmpuga@gmail.com.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Arantes</LastName><ForeName>Franciel Jos&#xe9;</ForeName><Initials>FJ</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Faculty of Electrical Engineering, Federal University of Uberlandia, Uberlandia, MG, Brazil. Electronic address: franciel_arantes@hotmail.com.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Oliveira</LastName><ForeName>Carlo Jos&#xe9; Freire</ForeName><Initials>CJF</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Institute of Biological and Natural Sciences, Federal University of Tri&#xe2;ngulo Mineiro, Uberaba, MG, Brazil. Electronic address: carlo@icbn.uftm.edu.br.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Cunha</LastName><ForeName>Lucas Moreira</ForeName>